			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_9 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">10 of 13</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><div class="mceTemp"></div>
<p style="text-align: left;">Sometimes Mayor Daley found creative solutions to the city&#8217;s building challenges. Click on the image of A. Robert Abboud to play video.</p>

<!-- iframe plugin v.4.3 wordpress.org/plugins/iframe/ -->
<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/_4UzChdJ7ek" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" 0="allowfullscreen" scrolling="yes" class="iframe-class"></iframe>

<p style="text-align: right;"> Video: <em>A. Robert Abboud, First National Bank of Chicago, President, interview excerpt, December 3, 2009</em></p>
<div id="attachment_979" style="width: 243px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_016.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-979 size-medium" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_016-233x300.jpg" alt="Construction of the First National Bank Plaza (3 shots), 1971. RJD_04_01_0033_0002_016" width="233" height="300" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_016-233x300.jpg 233w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_016-795x1024.jpg 795w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_016-1080x1391.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_016.jpg 1165w" sizes="(max-width: 233px) 100vw, 233px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Construction of the First National Bank Plaza (3 shots), 1971. RJD_04_01_0033_0002_016</p></div></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
				</div> <!-- .et_pb_container -->
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide -->
			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_10 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">11 of 13</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><p style="text-align: left;">To pay for Chicago&#8217;s services, Daley secured funds from a variety of sources. He used the city&#8217;s taxing authority when necessary, but he also wanted to ensure Chicago retained control of how that money was spent. That part of his job became easier when the new Illinois Constitution of 1970 granted home rule status to the city. Home rule meant that Chicago enjoyed greater discretion of when and how to tax, regulate, and perform certain services.</p>
<div id="attachment_983" style="width: 782px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0047_0006_026.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-983" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0047_0006_026-1024x823.jpg" alt="Richard J. Daley listening to a speaker at the Illinois General Assembly." width="772" height="621" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0047_0006_026-1024x823.jpg 1024w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0047_0006_026-300x241.jpg 300w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0047_0006_026-1080x868.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0047_0006_026.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 772px) 100vw, 772px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Richard J. Daley listening to a speaker at the Illinois General Assembly. This photo was likely taken in 1950, five years before he became mayor. RJD_04_01_0047_0006_026</p></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote>
<p style="text-align: left;">So the mayor wanted to keep Chicago’s taxing authority and Chicago’s ability to regulate independent of the General Assembly. So rather than trying to pass off responsibility to suburban communities or to county government, he wanted to centralize control in the city of Chicago&#8230;.He didn’t want municipal functions to be broadened out into the region or the county. He wasn’t trying to save taxpayers money by diverting responsibilities for the various city functions to the broader governmental agencies.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>Ray Simon, Corporation Counsel City of Chicago, interview excerpt, June 30, 2010</em></p>
</blockquote></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
				</div> <!-- .et_pb_container -->
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide -->
			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_11 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">12 of 13</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><p style="text-align: left;">Federal aid was important. Daley worked with Illinois&#8217;s congressional delegation to ensure Chicago received its share of national revenue.</p>
<div id="attachment_967" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0019_0009_004.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-967 size-medium" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0019_0009_004-300x236.jpg" alt="Richard J. Daley on his way to a congressional dinner, 1960. RJD_04_01_0019_0009_004" width="300" height="236" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0019_0009_004-300x236.jpg 300w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0019_0009_004-1024x806.jpg 1024w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0019_0009_004-1080x850.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0019_0009_004.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Richard J. Daley on his way to a congressional dinner, 1960. RJD_04_01_0019_0009_004</p></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id="attachment_964" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0016_0001_012.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-964 size-medium" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0016_0001_012-300x241.jpg" alt="Richard J. Daley shaking hands with Congressman Dan Rostenkowski, ca. 1960s. RJD_04_01_0016_0001_012" width="300" height="241" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0016_0001_012-300x241.jpg 300w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0016_0001_012-1024x823.jpg 1024w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0016_0001_012-1080x868.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0016_0001_012.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Richard J. Daley shaking hands with Congressman Dan Rostenkowski, ca. 1960s. RJD_04_01_0016_0001_012</p></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote>
<p style="text-align: left;">He was very shrewd in his relationship with Washington, D.C. He had a close relationship with Dan Rostenkowski, who was Chairman of Appropriations. Rostenkowski helped get him get the money to build the expressways, like the Dan Ryan and the improvements on the Kennedy. He was very much interested in transportation.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>Burton Natarus, Attorney and Alderman from the 42nd Ward from 1971-2007. Interview excerpt, June 16, 2010</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em> </em></p></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
